We apply the whitening test to this residuals matrix in order to know if it is useful to whiten the observations or not

whitening_test(residuals)

P value est trop forte donc on peut pas refuser h0

whitening_choice(residuals,c("AR1","nonparam","ARMA"),pAR=1,qMA=0)

Anova spare, mtabolite par mtabolite

select_per_anova=c()
for(i in 2:ncol(table2)){
  res.anova<-lm(table2[,i]~table2[,1], data=table2)
  pvalue.anova=c()
  pvalue.anova<-anova(res.anova)$'Pr(>F)'[1]
  if(pvalue.anova<0.005/q){
    select_per_anova=c(select_per_anova,colnames(table2)[i])}}
length(select_per_anova)
## [1] 85

Que les pvalues sont fortes bah on peut utiliser les 2. On pourrait tester avec des param du style AR31

The non parametric choice has the highest p-value. We select this dependence to model the residuals. We compute the square root of the inverse of the estimator of the covariance matrix of each row of the residuals matrix using the non parametric modelling as follows:

square_root_inv_hat_Sigma=whitening(residuals,"no_whitening",pAR=1,qMA=0)

# Estimation de sigma chapeau - 1/2 
# La mthode "nonparam" indique que la mthode de blanchiment sera non paramtrique. Les paramtres pAR et qMA dterminent le nombre de paramtres autoregressifs et de moyennes mobiles  utiliser dans le modle, et ici ils sont dfinis  1 et 0 respectivement.

Yvec=as.numeric(Yscaled%*%square_root_inv_hat_Sigma) 
Xvec=kronecker(t(square_root_inv_hat_Sigma),B) 
Xvec_sel=as.matrix(Xvec[,indices]) 
B_sel_hat=solve(t(Xvec_sel)%*%Xvec_sel,t(Xvec_sel)%*%Yvec) 
Freqs2$estim=rep(0,p*q) 
Freqs2$estim[indices]=as.vector(B_sel_hat)

Comparaison des rsultats slectionns

Insert_selected_variable <- function(dataframe, name, path_to_file) {
  load(path_to_file)
  seuil <- sort(Freqs2$frequency,decreasing = T)[nrow(dataframe)]
  var = Freqs2$Names_of_Y[Freqs2$frequency>=seuil]
  dataframe[name] = var[1:nrow(dataframe)]
  return(dataframe)
}
